<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-530-608  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 530 608.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Microprocessor Report  May 30 1990 v4 n10 p4(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT MicroDesign Resources Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Intel loses suit against lawyers, consultant. (Most SignificantBits) (column)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Intel Corp. (cases)Skjerven, Morrill, MacPherson, Franklin and Friel (cases).andO;Ticker:    INTC.andO;Topic:     Semiconductor IndustryLaw SuitLegal IssuesProprietary Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>The law firm of Skjerven, Morrill, MacPherson, Franklin andamp; Friel, andconsultant Robert Wedig, can now breathe a little easier.andP;  The firm and Wedighad been sued by Intel as part of the litigation surrounding ULSI Technology,but on May 8, the judge granted a Summary Judgment ending the suit.andM;This was one of the more unusual high-tech suits; rarely do the lawyers, andthe lawyers' consultants, get sued.andP;  To understand what happened here, somebackground is needed.andP;  Ex-Intel employee Alfred Chan went to work for startupULSI Technology, and brought with him a collection of Intel proprietarydocuments, including the 387 &quot;T-spec&quot; (target specification).andP;  ULSI presidentGeorge Hwang returned the documents to Intel, through ULSI's law firmSkierven, Morrill).andP;  The law firm showed the documents to Wedig so he couldhelp them understand their significance, agreed with Intel to keep themsecret, and kept a copy in their possession to document what they hadreturned.andM;Skjerven, Morrill then allegedly allowed another law firm, Townsend andTownsend, to see the documents as part of a clean room audit.andP;  Intel claimedthat this violated Skjerven, Morrill's promise to keep them secret.andP;  BothSkjerven, Morrill and Wedig have been involved in creating clean-roomprocedures for companies designing Intel-compatible chips.andP;  Intel filed suitagainst them in early '89, seeking to ensure that information from themisappropriated documents did not end up getting used to develop competitiveproducts.andP;  The proceedings got rather nasty, with Wedig and Townsend andTownsend refusing to answer some questions during depositions by Intel'sattorneys.andM;Along with the summary judgment, the judge denied Intel's request to forceWedig to answer questions about who his clients were, but ruled that Townsendand Townsend must answer questions about what documents they saw.andM;The source of Intel's sensitivity is apparently the protocol between the 386and the 387.andP;  Why they should be so concerned about this is a bit of amystery, since Cyrix and IIT, both of which are manufacturing 387-compatiblechips, have obviously figured it out.andP;  It is not, however, publiclydocumented.andP;  The 386 and 387 data sheets describe the signals and theirtiming, but not the protocol of the communication between the two devices.andO;</TEXT></DOC>